<h2>Implementing The Action Plan</h2>
<div id="links"><IMG SRC="/edu/vehicle_fires/images/VF-Figure8.jpg" border="1" ALIGN="right">
<ul>
<li>Check for occupants.</li>
<li>Use the right size hoseline (minimum 1-1/2 inch).</li>
<li>Use Class A foam.</li>
<li>Consider exposure protection.</li>
<li>Crew leader attacks from a distance with a straight stream to get a quick knockdown, while the crew is getting ready. </li>
<li>The attack crew deploys with full PPE with SCBA.</li>
<li>Attack the fire using the proper <a href="#">attack sequence<span><ol><li>Approach the vehicle at a 45-degree angle from the front or rear.</li>
<li>Using a narrow fog pattern, cool vehicle undercarriage, including the fuel tank, drive shaft, automatic transmission, catalytic converter and any affected energy-absorbing bumper system. </li>
<li>Cool the tires, wheels, suspension system</li>
<li>Cool engine compartment. Keep hood low to reduce oxygen supply to fire. Cool bumper assembly before working in front.</li></ol>
</span></a>.</li>
<li>Consider deploying a backup hoseline. </li>
<li>Check for occupants.</li>
<li>Secure the vehicle with wheel chocks as soon as practically possible.</li>
</ul>
